To establish an efficient algorithm, having a O(&#119896;log&#119899;) time complexity, we could follow these guidelines:

* In one iteration of the binary-search loop no more than *k* zero values should be visited;
* The same (zero) value should not be visited more than once

An idea would be to look &quot;around&quot; the `mid` index that the binary search algorithm would determine, looking for a non-zero value. So we would first look at `a[mid]`, then `a[mid-1]` `a[mid+1]` `a[mid-2]`, ...etc. If this search gets out of the `low..high` range, then this means there is no non-zero value in that range and the search should return -1 (failure)

When the `low..high` range is narrowed down, then this should exclude the zeroes that were already checked. 

Here is an implementation:

```java
    public static int kAlmostSearch(int[] a, int num) {
        int low = 0;
        int high = a.length;
        
        while (low &lt; high) {
            int mid = (low + high) / 2;
            // Look around for non zero value:
            int m = mid, add = -1;
            while (a[m] == 0) {
                m += add;
                // If there is no non-zero value in the range [low, high): not found
                if (m &lt; low || m &gt;= high) return -1;
                add = -add + (add &gt; 0 ? -1 : 1);
            }
            if (a[m] == num) return mid;
            // When narrowing the window, make sure to exclude the zeroes we already saw
            if (num &lt; a[m]) {
                high = Math.min(m, mid);
            } else {
                low = Math.max(m, mid) + 1;
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
```

NB: In this code, `high` is such that `a[high]` is not part of the current range.

