answers.body_markdown:
&gt; My code is working correctly only when input string length is of size 2 or 3.

It doesn&#39;t actually work for some inputs with size 3. The reason is that your code never modifies the characters in the result other than at the first and last index. So the character at index 1 (for when the input has size 3) is never modified after its initialisation to &#39;b&#39;. So for the example inputs with size 3 it is just luck that it works, but as soon as the expected output has another letter than &#39;b&#39; at index 1, your solution does not work for size 3 either.

The key insight here, is that the optimal character at index `i` is the **median** of all characters found at that index, and at the mirrored index (so counting backwards from the end of the string).

Here is an implementation:

```java
    static String solve(List&lt;String&gt; list) {
        int n = list.size();
        int m = list.get(0).length();
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        // Collect characters for the left half of the palindrome
        for (int i = 0, mid = (m + 1) / 2; i &lt; mid; i++) {
            // Count the occurrences of all characters at this index and the mirrored index
            int[] counter = new int[26];
            int j = m - 1 - i;
            for (String word : list) {
                counter[word.charAt(i) - &#39;a&#39;]++;
                counter[word.charAt(j) - &#39;a&#39;]++;
            }
            // Get the median character based on these character frequencies
            int median = -1;
            for (int total = 0; total &lt; n; total += counter[median]) {
                median++;
            }
            // Append this median to the palindrome
            sb.append((char)(median + (int)&#39;a&#39;));
        }
        // Complete the half of the palindrome with the other half
        return sb.toString() + sb.reverse().substring(m % 2);
    }    
```

